---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import ChapterNav from "../components/ChapterNav.astro";
---

<Layout title="Spring Boot Setup & Multi-Profile Configuration - SYP">
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-12 md:py-20">
        <a
            href="/syp-overview"
            class="mb-8 inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
            <span class="mr-2">&larr;</span>
            Back to SYP Overview
        </a>

        <article>
            <header class="mb-12">
                <h1
                    class="mb-4 text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl text-white"
                >
                    Spring Boot Setup & Multi-Profile Configuration
                </h1>
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-400">
                    Configuring a production-ready Spring Boot 3.4.5 application
                    with environment-specific settings
                </p>
            </header>

            <section class="prose prose-invert max-w-none space-y-8">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Overview</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
                        Every real-world application needs different
                        configurations for development, testing, and production.
                        This module covers how we structured the SYP project to
                        handle multiple environments seamlessly using Spring
                        profiles, Maven configuration, and environment
                        variables.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Learning Journey
                    </h2>
                    <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🔧 Challenge: Managing Multiple Environments
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Initially, everyone had different local database
                                connections. Learned to use Spring profiles so
                                each developer could have their own setup
                                without conflicting configurations.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🔐 Challenge: Secrets Management
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Database passwords, email credentials, and API
                                keys shouldn't be in source code. Implemented
                                environment variables that override YAML configs
                                for sensitive data.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                📊 Challenge: Data Consistency
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Production needs real data, development needs
                                test data. Used separate SQL scripts for each
                                environment and conditional loading based on
                                profile.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                ✅ Key Learning
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Proper configuration management prevents hours
                                of debugging caused by "works on my machine"
                                issues. Environment separation is crucial for
                                team collaboration.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Key Implementation
                    </h2>

                    <div class="mb-6">
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Maven POM Configuration
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`<!-- pom.xml - Spring Boot 3.4.5 with MS SQL Server -->
<parent>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-parent</artifactId>
    <version>3.4.5</version>
</parent>

<dependencies>
    <!-- Web & REST API -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    
    <!-- Database & ORM -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-data-jpa</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>com.microsoft.sqlserver</groupId>
        <artifactId>mssql-jdbc</artifactId>
        <version>12.6.1.jre11</version>
    </dependency>
    
    <!-- Security & JWT -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-security</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    
    <!-- Email -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-mail</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    
    <!-- WebSockets -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-websocket</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    
    <!-- Testing -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-test</artifactId>
        <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            Covers web, JPA, MS SQL, security, email, and
                            WebSockets—all managed by Spring Boot starters.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="mb-6">
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Application YAML - Profile Configuration
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`# application.yaml - Default Profile
spring:
  config:
    activate:
      on-profile: default
  jpa:
    open-in-view: false
    hibernate:
      ddl-auto: update
    properties:
      hikari:
        shutdown-timeout: 10000
  sql:
    init:
      mode: never
      data-locations: classpath:db/import-test.sql

# Database from environment variables
spring.datasource.url: \${TEST_DB_URL}
spring.datasource.username: \${TEST_DB_USERNAME}
spring.datasource.password: \${TEST_DB_PASSWORD}
spring.datasource.driver-class-name: com.microsoft.sqlserver.jdbc.SQLServerDriver

# Email: Local Papercut for Testing
spring.mail:
  host: 127.0.0.1
  port: 2525
  username:
  password:
  properties:
    mail:
      smtp:
        auth: false

---
# Production Profile
spring:
  config:
    activate:
      on-profile: production
  jpa:
    open-in-view: false
    hibernate:
      ddl-auto: validate
    properties:
      hikari:
        shutdown-timeout: 30000
        maximum-pool-size: 20
  sql:
    init:
      mode: never

# Production Database
spring.datasource.url: \${PROD_DB_URL}
spring.datasource.username: \${PROD_DB_USERNAME}
spring.datasource.password: \${PROD_DB_PASSWORD}

# Production Email Service
spring.mail:
  host: \${MAIL_HOST}
  port: \${MAIL_PORT}
  username: \${MAIL_USERNAME}
  password: \${MAIL_PASSWORD}`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            Spring profiles allow completely different
                            configurations. Production uses <code>validate</code
                            > mode (won't auto-update schema) and larger connection
                            pools.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Docker & Environment Variables
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`# Dockerfile
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
COPY target/spring-boot-jwt-auth.jar app.jar
ENTRYPOINT ["java", "-jar", "app.jar"]

# .env file (for Docker Compose)
SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=production
TEST_DB_URL=jdbc:sqlserver://db:1433;databaseName=syp
TEST_DB_USERNAME=sa
TEST_DB_PASSWORD=YourSecurePassword123!
MAIL_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
MAIL_PORT=587
MAIL_USERNAME=\${GMAIL_USER}
MAIL_PASSWORD=\${GMAIL_APP_PASSWORD}

# Run command with profile
java -jar app.jar --spring.profiles.active=production`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            Environment variables override YAML configs,
                            preventing secrets from ending up in source code.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Technology Stack
                    </h2>
                    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
                        {
                            [
                                "Spring Boot 3.4.5",
                                "Maven",
                                "YAML Configuration",
                                "Environment Variables",
                                "Docker",
                                "MS SQL Server",
                            ].map((tech) => (
                                <span class="rounded-full border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-500/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-indigo-300">
                                    {tech}
                                </span>
                            ))
                        }
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Results & Impact
                    </h2>
                    <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300">
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>No Configuration Conflicts:</strong> Each
                                developer and environment has isolated settings</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Secrets Not in Code:</strong> Passwords and
                                API keys come from environment, never committed</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Reproducible Environments:</strong> Same
                                configs work on laptop, CI/CD pipeline, and production</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Team Collaboration:</strong> Everyone can
                                focus on code, not wrestling with configuration</span
                            >
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </section>
            <ChapterNav
                prevLink="/syp-overview"
                prevText="Project Overview"
                nextLink="/syp-service-layer"
                nextText="Service Layer Architecture"
            />
        </article>
    </main>
</Layout>
